HEADWORD: Crasis
<hw>Cra"sis</hw> <pr>(kr?"s?s)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[LL.,
temperament, fr. Gr. <?/<?/<?/<?/, fr. <?/<?/<?/<?/ to mix.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A mixture of constituents, as of the
blood; constitution; temperament.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Gram.)</fld> <def>A contraction of two vowels (as
the final and initial vowels of united words) into one long vowel, or
into a diphthong; syn⟦ae⟧resis; as, <xex>cogo</xex> for
<xex>coago</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Craspedota</ent>⟦br⟧
